          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">Austria forms a coalition</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/austrian-government-swearing-in-vienna-beate-meinl-reisinger-christian-stocker-alexander-van-der-bellen-andreas-babler.png" alt="Austrian Minister of Foreign Affairs Beate Meinl-Reisinger, Chancellor Christian Stocker, President Alexander Van der Bellen, and Vice Chancellor Andreas Babler during the swearing-in of the new government in Vienna" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">Austrian Minister of Foreign Affairs Beate Meinl-Reisinger, Chancellor Christian Stocker, President Alexander Van der Bellen, and Vice Chancellor Andreas Babler during the swearing-in of the new government in Vienna. Credits: Roland Schlager/AFP</p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
         
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Austria’s coalition government has taken office after months of political uncertainty. It will comprise the conservative ÖVP, center-left SPÖ, and liberal NEOS. The <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-04-03-2024-h1-1-the-far-right-was-blocked-from-power?source=website" target="_blank">far-right FPÖ was ultimately blocked from power</a> after coalition talks with the ÖVP collapsed. Christian Stocker, who became the chancellor, will lead the government. The coalition was sealed when Austria's NEOS party signed the 200-page agreement.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">The NEOS secured their first-ever role in a national government. NEOS will be in charge of the Foreign and Education Ministries. The coalition also plans tighter migration rules and austerity measures to tackle the budget deficit. Austria endured the longest wait since World War II to form this government. FPÖ leader Herbert Kickl criticized the new coalition and called for a snap election.
       </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Meanwhile, Germany faces a similar challenge in forming a government after its recent elections. Center-right CDU leader Friedrich Merz is set to begin coalition talks with Chancellor Olaf Scholz’s Social Democrats.
</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
