          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Africa HIV deaths to mount with Trump’s cuts</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;"><strong>Summary: Trump’s suspension of USAID programs is affecting HIV and AIDS treatment in Africa, particularly South Africa.</strong></p>

          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Many African countries are starting to feel the brunt of the suspension of USAID programs. <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-04-03-2025-h3-3-funding-has-been-put-on-hold-for-hiv-aids-programs?source=website" target="_blank">Funding has been put on hold for HIV/AIDS programs</a> in Africa, threatening treatment access for millions. Experts warn that these cuts could lead to hundreds of deaths. South Africa is particularly affected, where 500,000 deaths are projected over the next decade. It has 7.4 million people living with HIV.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">The funding halts came after President Trump’s executive order paused foreign aid, leading to a 90% reduction in USAID contracts. The US has also withdrawn support from UNAIDS. This affects HIV services in over 55 countries, with Africa hit hardest. Clinics are closing, testing services are vanishing, and many have lost access to antiretroviral therapy (ART).</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Other affected nations include Mozambique, Tanzania, and Ivory Coast, where hundreds of HIV clinics have shut down. Some African governments are seeking local solutions. South Africa has launched an HIV Treatment Campaign, and Nigeria has allocated $3.3 Mn to fill short-term funding gaps. Experts urge the EU and private foundations like the Gates Foundation to step in. </p>
        </mj-text>
    </mj-section>
