          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
            <strong>🇪🇺 EU asylum requests were down by 11% in 2024, says EUAA</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">According to the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-04-03-2025-br1-4-european-union-agency-for-asylum?source=website" target="_blank">European Union Agency for Asylum</a>, asylum applications in the EU, Norway, and Switzerland fell by 11% in 2024 to 1,014,420 but remained above one million for the second consecutive year. Nearly half (48%) came from nationalities with low approval rates, prompting calls for faster deportations and "return hubs" outside EU borders. The largest applicant groups were Syrians, Afghans, Venezuelans, Turks, and Colombians.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Germany led with 237,000 applications, followed by Spain, Italy, and France. The approval rate was 42%, with Syrians (90%) and Malians (84%) being the most successful. Despite a 38% drop in irregular border crossings, pending cases reached 981,000. This matched the 2016 crisis levels, as most applicants arrived through legal channels instead.</p>
        </mj-text>
